{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"Thank you so much. I'm going to try to take you"},{"time":3000,"text":"on a journey of the underwater acoustic world"},{"time":6000,"text":"of whales and dolphins."},{"time":8000,"text":"Since we are such a visual species,"},{"time":10000,"text":"it's hard for us to really understand this,"},{"time":12000,"text":"so I'll use a mixture of figures and sounds"},{"time":14000,"text":"and hope this can communicate it."},{"time":16000,"text":"But let's also think, as a visual species,"},{"time":19000,"text":"what it's like when we go snorkeling or diving"},{"time":21000,"text":"and try to look underwater."},{"time":23000,"text":"We really can't see very far."},{"time":25000,"text":"Our vision, which works so well in air,"},{"time":27000,"text":"all of a sudden is very restricted and claustrophobic."},{"time":30000,"text":"And what marine mammals have evolved"},{"time":32000,"text":"over the last tens of millions of years"},{"time":35000,"text":"is ways to depend on sound"},{"time":37000,"text":"to both explore their world"},{"time":39000,"text":"and also to stay in touch with one another."}]},{"cues":[{"time":41000,"text":"Dolphins and toothed whales use echolocation."},{"time":43000,"text":"They can produce loud clicks"},{"time":45000,"text":"and listen for echoes from the sea floor in order to orient."},{"time":48000,"text":"They can listen for echoes from prey"},{"time":50000,"text":"in order to decide where food is"},{"time":52000,"text":"and to decide which one they want to eat."},{"time":55000,"text":"All marine mammals use sound for communication to stay in touch."},{"time":57000,"text":"So the large baleen whales"},{"time":59000,"text":"will produce long, beautiful songs,"},{"time":62000,"text":"which are used in reproductive advertisement"},{"time":64000,"text":"for male and females, both to find one another"},{"time":66000,"text":"and to select a mate."},{"time":68000,"text":"And mother and young and closely bonded animals"},{"time":70000,"text":"use calls to stay in touch with one another,"},{"time":73000,"text":"so sound is really critical for their lives."}]},{"cues":[{"time":75000,"text":"The first thing that got me interested in the sounds"},{"time":77000,"text":"of these underwater animals,"},{"time":79000,"text":"whose world was so foreign to me,"},{"time":81000,"text":"was evidence from captive dolphins"},{"time":83000,"text":"that captive dolphins could imitate human sounds."},{"time":86000,"text":"And I mentioned I'll use"},{"time":88000,"text":"some visual representations of sounds."},{"time":90000,"text":"Here's the first example."},{"time":92000,"text":"This is a plot of frequency against time --"},{"time":94000,"text":"sort of like musical notation,"},{"time":96000,"text":"where the higher notes are up higher and the lower notes are lower,"},{"time":99000,"text":"and time goes this way."},{"time":101000,"text":"This is a picture of a trainer's whistle,"},{"time":103000,"text":"a whistle a trainer will blow to tell a dolphin"},{"time":105000,"text":"it's done the right thing and can come get a fish."},{"time":107000,"text":"It sounds sort of like \"tweeeeeet.\" Like that."},{"time":110000,"text":"This is a calf in captivity"},{"time":112000,"text":"making an imitation"},{"time":114000,"text":"of that trainer's whistle."},{"time":116000,"text":"If you hummed this tune to your dog or cat"},{"time":118000,"text":"and it hummed it back to you,"},{"time":120000,"text":"you ought to be pretty surprised."},{"time":122000,"text":"Very few nonhuman mammals"},{"time":124000,"text":"can imitate sounds."},{"time":126000,"text":"It's really important for our music and our language."}]},{"cues":[{"time":128000,"text":"So it's a puzzle: The few other mammal groups that do this,"},{"time":131000,"text":"why do they do it?"},{"time":133000,"text":"A lot of my career has been devoted"},{"time":135000,"text":"to trying to understand"},{"time":137000,"text":"how these animals use their learning,"},{"time":139000,"text":"use the ability to change what you say"},{"time":141000,"text":"based on what you hear"},{"time":143000,"text":"in their own communication systems."},{"time":145000,"text":"So let's start with calls of a nonhuman primate."},{"time":148000,"text":"Many mammals have to produce contact calls"},{"time":150000,"text":"when, say, a mother and calf are apart."},{"time":153000,"text":"This is an example of a call produced by squirrel monkeys"},{"time":156000,"text":"when they're isolated from another one."},{"time":158000,"text":"And you can see, there's not much"},{"time":160000,"text":"variability in these calls."},{"time":162000,"text":"By contrast, the signature whistle"},{"time":164000,"text":"which dolphins use to stay in touch,"},{"time":166000,"text":"each individual here has a radically different call."},{"time":169000,"text":"They can use this ability to learn calls"},{"time":172000,"text":"in order to develop more complicated and more distinctive calls"},{"time":175000,"text":"to identify individuals."}]},{"cues":[{"time":178000,"text":"How about the setting in which animals need to use this call?"},{"time":181000,"text":"Well let's look at mothers and calves."},{"time":183000,"text":"In normal life for mother and calf dolphin,"},{"time":185000,"text":"they'll often drift apart or swim apart if Mom is chasing a fish,"},{"time":188000,"text":"and when they separate"},{"time":190000,"text":"they have to get back together again."},{"time":192000,"text":"What this figure shows is the percentage of the separations"},{"time":195000,"text":"in which dolphins whistle,"},{"time":197000,"text":"against the maximum distance."},{"time":199000,"text":"So when dolphins are separating by less than 20 meters,"},{"time":201000,"text":"less than half the time they need to use whistles."},{"time":203000,"text":"Most of the time they can just find each other"},{"time":205000,"text":"just by swimming around."},{"time":207000,"text":"But all of the time when they separate by more than 100 meters,"},{"time":210000,"text":"they need to use these individually distinctive whistles"},{"time":213000,"text":"to come back together again."},{"time":216000,"text":"Most of these distinctive signature whistles"},{"time":218000,"text":"are quite stereotyped and stable"},{"time":220000,"text":"through the life of a dolphin."},{"time":222000,"text":"But there are some exceptions."}]},{"cues":[{"time":224000,"text":"When a male dolphin leaves Mom,"},{"time":226000,"text":"it will often join up with another male"},{"time":228000,"text":"and form an alliance, which may last for decades."},{"time":231000,"text":"As these two animals form a social bond,"},{"time":234000,"text":"their distinctive whistles actually converge"},{"time":236000,"text":"and become very similar."},{"time":238000,"text":"This plot shows two members of a pair."},{"time":241000,"text":"As you can see at the top here,"},{"time":243000,"text":"they share an up-sweep, like \"woop, woop, woop.\""},{"time":245000,"text":"They both have that kind of up-sweep."},{"time":247000,"text":"Whereas these members of a pair go \"wo-ot, wo-ot, wo-ot.\""},{"time":250000,"text":"And what's happened is"},{"time":252000,"text":"they've used this learning process"},{"time":254000,"text":"to develop a new sign that identifies this new social group."},{"time":257000,"text":"It's a very interesting way that they can"},{"time":259000,"text":"form a new identifier"},{"time":261000,"text":"for the new social group that they've had."}]},{"cues":[{"time":263000,"text":"Let's now take a step back"},{"time":265000,"text":"and see what this message can tell us"},{"time":267000,"text":"about protecting dolphins"},{"time":269000,"text":"from human disturbance."},{"time":271000,"text":"Anybody looking at this picture"},{"time":273000,"text":"will know this dolphin is surrounded,"},{"time":275000,"text":"and clearly his behavior is being disrupted."},{"time":278000,"text":"This is a bad situation."},{"time":280000,"text":"But it turns out that when just a single boat"},{"time":282000,"text":"is approaching a group of dolphins"},{"time":284000,"text":"at a couple hundred meters away,"},{"time":286000,"text":"the dolphins will start whistling,"},{"time":288000,"text":"they'll change what they're doing, they'll have a more cohesive group,"},{"time":290000,"text":"wait for the boat to go by,"},{"time":292000,"text":"and then they'll get back to normal business."},{"time":294000,"text":"Well, in a place like Sarasota, Florida,"},{"time":296000,"text":"the average interval between times"},{"time":298000,"text":"that a boat is passing within a hundred meters of a dolphin group"},{"time":301000,"text":"is six minutes."},{"time":303000,"text":"So even in the situation that doesn't look as bad as this,"},{"time":306000,"text":"it's still affecting the amount of time these animals have"},{"time":308000,"text":"to do their normal work."}]},{"cues":[{"time":310000,"text":"And if we look at a very pristine environment like western Australia,"},{"time":313000,"text":"Lars Bider has done work"},{"time":315000,"text":"comparing dolphin behavior and distribution"},{"time":318000,"text":"before there were dolphin-watching boats."},{"time":321000,"text":"When there was one boat, not much of an impact."},{"time":324000,"text":"And two boats: When the second boat was added,"},{"time":327000,"text":"what happened was that some of the dolphins"},{"time":329000,"text":"left the area completely."},{"time":331000,"text":"Of the ones that stayed, their reproductive rate declined."},{"time":334000,"text":"So it could have a negative impact on the whole population."},{"time":337000,"text":"When we think of marine-protected areas for animals like dolphins,"},{"time":340000,"text":"this means that we have to be"},{"time":342000,"text":"quite conscious about activities that we thought were benign."},{"time":345000,"text":"We may need to regulate the intensity"},{"time":347000,"text":"of recreational boating and actual whale watching"},{"time":350000,"text":"in order to prevent these kinds of problems."},{"time":353000,"text":"I'd also like to point out that sound"},{"time":355000,"text":"doesn't obey boundaries."},{"time":357000,"text":"So you can draw a line to try to protect an area,"},{"time":360000,"text":"but chemical pollution and noise pollution"},{"time":362000,"text":"will continue to move through the area."}]},{"cues":[{"time":364000,"text":"And I'd like to switch now from this local,"},{"time":366000,"text":"familiar, coastal environment"},{"time":369000,"text":"to a much broader world of the baleen whales and the open ocean."},{"time":372000,"text":"This is a kind of map we've all been looking at."},{"time":375000,"text":"The world is mostly blue."},{"time":377000,"text":"But I'd also like to point out that the oceans"},{"time":379000,"text":"are much more connected than we think."},{"time":381000,"text":"Notice how few barriers there are to movement"},{"time":384000,"text":"across all of the oceans compared to land."},{"time":386000,"text":"To me, the most mind-bending example"},{"time":388000,"text":"of the interconnectedness of the ocean"},{"time":390000,"text":"comes from an acoustic experiment"},{"time":392000,"text":"where oceanographers"},{"time":394000,"text":"took a ship to the southern Indian Ocean,"},{"time":397000,"text":"deployed an underwater loudspeaker"},{"time":399000,"text":"and played back a sound."},{"time":401000,"text":"That same sound"},{"time":403000,"text":"traveled to the west, and could be heard in Bermuda,"},{"time":406000,"text":"and traveled to the east, and could be heard in Monterey --"},{"time":409000,"text":"the same sound."}]},{"cues":[{"time":411000,"text":"So we live in a world of satellite communication,"},{"time":413000,"text":"are used to global communication,"},{"time":415000,"text":"but it's still amazing to me."},{"time":417000,"text":"The ocean has properties"},{"time":419000,"text":"that allow low-frequency sound"},{"time":421000,"text":"to basically move globally."},{"time":423000,"text":"The acoustic transit time for each of these paths is about three hours."},{"time":426000,"text":"It's nearly halfway around the globe."},{"time":429000,"text":"In the early '70s,"},{"time":431000,"text":"Roger Payne and an ocean acoustician"},{"time":433000,"text":"published a theoretical paper"},{"time":435000,"text":"pointing out that it was possible"},{"time":437000,"text":"that sound could transmit over these large areas,"},{"time":440000,"text":"but very few biologists believed it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":443000,"text":"It actually turns out, though,"},{"time":445000,"text":"even though we've only known of long-range propagation for a few decades,"},{"time":448000,"text":"the whales clearly have evolved,"},{"time":451000,"text":"over tens of millions of years,"},{"time":453000,"text":"a way to exploit this amazing property of the ocean."},{"time":456000,"text":"So blue whales and fin whales"},{"time":458000,"text":"produce very low-frequency sounds"},{"time":460000,"text":"that can travel over very long ranges."},{"time":462000,"text":"The top plot here shows"},{"time":464000,"text":"a complicated series of calls"},{"time":466000,"text":"that are repeated by males."},{"time":468000,"text":"They form songs, and they appear to play a role in reproduction,"},{"time":471000,"text":"sort of like that of song birds."},{"time":473000,"text":"Down below here, we see calls made by both males and females"},{"time":476000,"text":"that also carry over very long ranges."}]},{"cues":[{"time":480000,"text":"The biologists continued to be skeptical"},{"time":482000,"text":"of the long-range communication issue"},{"time":484000,"text":"well past the '70s,"},{"time":486000,"text":"until the end of the Cold War."},{"time":488000,"text":"What happened was, during the Cold War,"},{"time":490000,"text":"the U.S. Navy had a system that was secret at the time,"},{"time":493000,"text":"that they used to track Russian submarines."},{"time":496000,"text":"It had deep underwater microphones, or hydrophones,"},{"time":498000,"text":"cabled to shore,"},{"time":500000,"text":"all wired back to a central place that could listen"},{"time":502000,"text":"to sounds over the whole North Atlantic."},{"time":504000,"text":"And after the Berlin Wall fell, the Navy made these systems available"},{"time":507000,"text":"to whale bio-acousticians"},{"time":509000,"text":"to see what they could hear."}]},{"cues":[{"time":511000,"text":"This is a plot from Christopher Clark"},{"time":513000,"text":"who tracked one individual blue whale"},{"time":516000,"text":"as it passed by Bermuda,"},{"time":518000,"text":"went down to the latitude of Miami and came back again."},{"time":521000,"text":"It was tracked for 43 days,"},{"time":523000,"text":"swimming 1,700 kilometers,"},{"time":525000,"text":"or more than 1,000 miles."},{"time":527000,"text":"This shows us both that the calls"},{"time":529000,"text":"are detectable over hundreds of miles"},{"time":531000,"text":"and that whales routinely swim hundreds of miles."},{"time":533000,"text":"They're ocean-based and scale animals"},{"time":535000,"text":"who are communicating over much longer ranges"},{"time":537000,"text":"than we had anticipated."}]},{"cues":[{"time":539000,"text":"Unlike fins and blues, which"},{"time":541000,"text":"disperse into the temperate and tropical oceans,"},{"time":543000,"text":"the humpbacked whales congregate"},{"time":545000,"text":"in local traditional breeding grounds,"},{"time":548000,"text":"so they can make a sound that's a little higher in frequency,"},{"time":551000,"text":"broader-band and more complicated."},{"time":553000,"text":"So you're listening to the complicated song"},{"time":555000,"text":"produced by humpbacks here."},{"time":557000,"text":"Humpbacks, when they develop"},{"time":559000,"text":"the ability to sing this song,"},{"time":561000,"text":"they're listening to other whales"},{"time":563000,"text":"and modifying what they sing based on what they're hearing,"},{"time":566000,"text":"just like song birds or the dolphin whistles I described."},{"time":569000,"text":"This means that humpback song"},{"time":571000,"text":"is a form of animal culture,"},{"time":573000,"text":"just like music for humans would be."}]},{"cues":[{"time":575000,"text":"I think one of the most interesting examples of this"},{"time":578000,"text":"comes from Australia."},{"time":580000,"text":"Biologists on the east coast of Australia"},{"time":582000,"text":"were recording the songs of humpbacks in that area."},{"time":585000,"text":"And this orange line here marks the typical songs"},{"time":588000,"text":"of east coast humpbacks."},{"time":590000,"text":"In '95 they all sang the normal song."},{"time":592000,"text":"But in '96 they heard a few weird songs,"},{"time":594000,"text":"and it turned out that these strange songs"},{"time":597000,"text":"were typical of west coast whales."},{"time":599000,"text":"The west coast calls became more and more popular,"},{"time":602000,"text":"until by 1998,"},{"time":604000,"text":"none of the whales sang the east coast song; it was completely gone."},{"time":607000,"text":"They just sang the cool new west coast song."},{"time":609000,"text":"It's as if some new hit style"},{"time":611000,"text":"had completely wiped out"},{"time":613000,"text":"the old-fashioned style before,"},{"time":615000,"text":"and with no golden oldies stations."},{"time":617000,"text":"Nobody sang the old ones."}]},{"cues":[{"time":620000,"text":"I'd like to briefly just show what the ocean does to these calls."},{"time":623000,"text":"Now you are listening to a recording made by Chris Clark,"},{"time":626000,"text":"0.2 miles away from a humpback."},{"time":629000,"text":"You can hear the full frequency range. It's quite loud."},{"time":632000,"text":"You sound very nearby."},{"time":634000,"text":"The next recording you're going to hear"},{"time":636000,"text":"was made of the same humpback song"},{"time":638000,"text":"50 miles away."},{"time":640000,"text":"That's shown down here."},{"time":642000,"text":"You only hear the low frequencies."},{"time":644000,"text":"You hear the reverberation"},{"time":646000,"text":"as the sound travels over long-range in the ocean"},{"time":648000,"text":"and is not quite as loud."},{"time":651000,"text":"Now after I play back these humpback calls,"},{"time":654000,"text":"I'll play blue whale calls, but they have to be sped up"},{"time":657000,"text":"because they're so low in frequency"},{"time":659000,"text":"that you wouldn't be able to hear it otherwise."},{"time":661000,"text":"Here's a blue whale call at 50 miles,"},{"time":663000,"text":"which was distant for the humpback."},{"time":665000,"text":"It's loud, clear -- you can hear it very clearly."},{"time":668000,"text":"Here's the same call recorded from a hydrophone"},{"time":671000,"text":"500 miles away."},{"time":673000,"text":"There's a lot of noise, which is mostly other whales."},{"time":676000,"text":"But you can still hear that faint call."}]},{"cues":[{"time":679000,"text":"Let's now switch and think about"},{"time":681000,"text":"a potential for human impacts."},{"time":683000,"text":"The most dominant sound that humans put into the ocean"},{"time":686000,"text":"comes from shipping."},{"time":688000,"text":"This is the sound of a ship,"},{"time":690000,"text":"and I'm having to talk a little louder to talk over it."},{"time":692000,"text":"Imagine that whale listening from 500 miles."},{"time":695000,"text":"There's a potential problem that maybe"},{"time":697000,"text":"this kind of shipping noise would prevent whales"},{"time":699000,"text":"from being able to hear each other."},{"time":701000,"text":"Now this is something that's been known for quite a while."}]},{"cues":[{"time":703000,"text":"This is a figure from a textbook on underwater sound."},{"time":706000,"text":"And on the y-axis"},{"time":708000,"text":"is the loudness of average ambient noise in the deep ocean"},{"time":711000,"text":"by frequency."},{"time":713000,"text":"In the low frequencies, this line indicates"},{"time":716000,"text":"sound that comes from seismic activity of the earth."},{"time":719000,"text":"Up high, these variable lines"},{"time":721000,"text":"indicate increasing noise in this frequency range"},{"time":724000,"text":"from higher wind and wave."},{"time":726000,"text":"But right in the middle here where there's a sweet spot,"},{"time":729000,"text":"the noise is dominated by human ships."},{"time":731000,"text":"Now think about it. This is an amazing thing:"},{"time":733000,"text":"That in this frequency range where whales communicate,"},{"time":736000,"text":"the main source globally, on our planet, for the noise"},{"time":739000,"text":"comes from human ships,"},{"time":741000,"text":"thousands of human ships, distant, far away,"},{"time":744000,"text":"just all aggregating."}]},{"cues":[{"time":746000,"text":"The next slide will show what the impact this may have"},{"time":749000,"text":"on the range at which whales can communicate."},{"time":751000,"text":"So here we have the loudness of a call at the whale."},{"time":754000,"text":"And as we get farther away,"},{"time":756000,"text":"the sound gets fainter and fainter."},{"time":758000,"text":"Now in the pre-industrial ocean, as we were mentioning,"},{"time":761000,"text":"this whale call could be easily detected."},{"time":763000,"text":"It's louder than noise"},{"time":765000,"text":"at a range of a thousand kilometers."},{"time":767000,"text":"Let's now take that additional increase in noise"},{"time":770000,"text":"that we saw comes from shipping."},{"time":772000,"text":"All of a sudden, the effective range of communication"},{"time":774000,"text":"goes from a thousand kilometers to 10 kilometers."},{"time":777000,"text":"Now if this signal is used for males and females"},{"time":779000,"text":"to find each other for mating and they're dispersed,"},{"time":782000,"text":"imagine the impact this could have"},{"time":784000,"text":"on the recovery of endangered populations."}]},{"cues":[{"time":787000,"text":"Whales also have contact calls"},{"time":789000,"text":"like I described for the dolphins."},{"time":792000,"text":"I'll play the sound of a contact call used"},{"time":794000,"text":"by right whales to stay in touch."},{"time":796000,"text":"And this is the kind of call that is used by,"},{"time":798000,"text":"say, right whale mothers and calves"},{"time":800000,"text":"as they separate to come back again."},{"time":802000,"text":"Now imagine -- let's put the ship noise in the picture."},{"time":804000,"text":"What's a mother to do"},{"time":806000,"text":"if the ship comes by and her calf isn't there?"},{"time":808000,"text":"I'll describe a couple strategies."}]},{"cues":[{"time":811000,"text":"One strategy is if your call's down here,"},{"time":813000,"text":"and the noise is in this band,"},{"time":815000,"text":"you could shift the frequency of your call out of the noise band"},{"time":818000,"text":"and communicate better."},{"time":820000,"text":"Susan Parks of Penn State has actually studied this."},{"time":823000,"text":"She's looked in the Atlantic. Here's data from the South Atlantic."},{"time":826000,"text":"Here's a typical South Atlantic contact call from the '70s."},{"time":829000,"text":"Look what happened by 2000 to the average call."},{"time":832000,"text":"Same thing in the North Atlantic,"},{"time":834000,"text":"in the '50s versus 2000."},{"time":836000,"text":"Over the last 50 years,"},{"time":838000,"text":"as we've put more noise into the oceans,"},{"time":840000,"text":"these whales have had to shift."},{"time":842000,"text":"It's as if the whole population had to shift"},{"time":844000,"text":"from being basses to singing as a tenor."},{"time":847000,"text":"It's an amazing shift, induced by humans"},{"time":849000,"text":"over this large scale,"},{"time":851000,"text":"in both time and space."}]},{"cues":[{"time":853000,"text":"And we now know that whales can compensate for noise"},{"time":855000,"text":"by calling louder, like I did when that ship was playing,"},{"time":858000,"text":"by waiting for silence"},{"time":860000,"text":"and by shifting their call out of the noise band."},{"time":863000,"text":"Now there's probably costs to calling louder"},{"time":865000,"text":"or shifting the frequency away from where you want to be,"},{"time":867000,"text":"and there's probably lost opportunities."},{"time":869000,"text":"If we also have to wait for silence,"},{"time":871000,"text":"they may miss a critical opportunity to communicate."},{"time":874000,"text":"So we have to be very concerned"},{"time":876000,"text":"about when the noise in habitats"},{"time":878000,"text":"degrades the habitat enough"},{"time":880000,"text":"that the animals either have to pay too much to be able to communicate,"},{"time":883000,"text":"or are not able to perform critical functions."},{"time":885000,"text":"It's a really important problem."}]},{"cues":[{"time":888000,"text":"And I'm happy to say that there are several"},{"time":890000,"text":"very promising developments in this area,"},{"time":893000,"text":"looking at the impact of shipping on whales."},{"time":896000,"text":"In terms of the shipping noise,"},{"time":898000,"text":"the International Maritime Organization of the United Nations"},{"time":901000,"text":"has formed a group whose job is to establish"},{"time":904000,"text":"guidelines for quieting ships,"},{"time":906000,"text":"to tell the industry how you could quiet ships."},{"time":908000,"text":"And they've already found"},{"time":910000,"text":"that by being more intelligent about better propeller design,"},{"time":913000,"text":"you can reduce that noise by 90 percent."},{"time":916000,"text":"If you actually insulate and isolate"},{"time":919000,"text":"the machinery of the ship from the hull,"},{"time":921000,"text":"you can reduce that noise by 99 percent."},{"time":924000,"text":"So at this point, it's primarily an issue of cost and standards."},{"time":927000,"text":"If this group can establish standards,"},{"time":929000,"text":"and if the shipbuilding industry adopts them for building new ships,"},{"time":932000,"text":"we can now see a gradual decline"},{"time":934000,"text":"in this potential problem."}]},{"cues":[{"time":936000,"text":"But there's also another problem from ships that I'm illustrating here,"},{"time":939000,"text":"and that's the problem of collision."},{"time":941000,"text":"This is a whale that just squeaked by"},{"time":944000,"text":"a rapidly moving container ship and avoided collision."},{"time":947000,"text":"But collision is a serious problem."},{"time":949000,"text":"Endangered whales are killed every year by ship collision,"},{"time":952000,"text":"and it's very important to try to reduce this."},{"time":955000,"text":"I'll discuss two very promising approaches."},{"time":958000,"text":"The first case comes from the Bay of Fundy."},{"time":960000,"text":"These black lines mark shipping lanes"},{"time":962000,"text":"in and out of the Bay of Fundy."},{"time":964000,"text":"The colorized area"},{"time":966000,"text":"shows the risk of collision for endangered right whales"},{"time":969000,"text":"because of the ships moving in this lane."},{"time":971000,"text":"It turns out that this lane here"},{"time":974000,"text":"goes right through a major feeding area of right whales in the summer time,"},{"time":977000,"text":"and it makes an area of a significant risk of collision."},{"time":980000,"text":"Well, biologists"},{"time":982000,"text":"who couldn't take no for an answer"},{"time":984000,"text":"went to the International Maritime Organization"},{"time":986000,"text":"and petitioned them to say,"},{"time":988000,"text":"\"Can't you move that lane? Those are just lines on the ground."},{"time":990000,"text":"Can't you move them over to a place"},{"time":992000,"text":"where there's less of a risk?\""},{"time":994000,"text":"And the International Maritime Organization responded very strongly,"},{"time":996000,"text":"\"These are the new lanes.\""},{"time":998000,"text":"The shipping lanes have been moved."},{"time":1000000,"text":"And as you can see, the risk of collision is much lower."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1003000,"text":"So it's very promising, actually."},{"time":1005000,"text":"We can be very creative about thinking"},{"time":1007000,"text":"of different ways to reduce these risks."},{"time":1009000,"text":"Another action which was just taken independently"},{"time":1011000,"text":"by a shipping company itself"},{"time":1014000,"text":"was initiated because of concerns the shipping company had"},{"time":1017000,"text":"about greenhouse gas emissions with global warming."},{"time":1020000,"text":"The Maersk Line looked at their competition"},{"time":1023000,"text":"and saw that everybody who is in shipping thinks time is money."},{"time":1026000,"text":"They rush as fast as they can to get to their port."},{"time":1028000,"text":"But then they often wait there."},{"time":1030000,"text":"What Maersk did is they worked ways to slow down."},{"time":1032000,"text":"They could slow down by about 50 percent."},{"time":1035000,"text":"This reduced their fuel consumption by about 30 percent,"},{"time":1038000,"text":"which saved them money,"},{"time":1040000,"text":"and at the same time, it had a significant benefit for whales."},{"time":1043000,"text":"It you slow down, you reduce the amount of noise you make"},{"time":1046000,"text":"and you reduce the risk of collision."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1048000,"text":"So to conclude, I'd just like to point out,"},{"time":1050000,"text":"you know, the whales live in"},{"time":1052000,"text":"an amazing acoustic environment."},{"time":1054000,"text":"They've evolved over tens of millions of years"},{"time":1056000,"text":"to take advantage of this."},{"time":1058000,"text":"And we need to be very attentive and vigilant"},{"time":1061000,"text":"to thinking about where things that we do"},{"time":1063000,"text":"may unintentionally prevent them"},{"time":1065000,"text":"from being able to achieve their important activities."},{"time":1068000,"text":"At the same time, we need to be really creative"},{"time":1070000,"text":"in thinking of solutions to be able to help reduce these problems."},{"time":1073000,"text":"I hope these examples have shown"},{"time":1075000,"text":"some of the different directions we can take"},{"time":1077000,"text":"in addition to protected areas"},{"time":1079000,"text":"to be able to keep the ocean safe for whales to be able to continue to communicate."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1082000,"text":"Thank you very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1084000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}